  "prompt": "What are the comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different nations?",
  "response": "Money laundering is a global issue, and different countries have developed varied legal approaches to combat this financial crime. Here's an overview of comparative legal approaches:\n\n1. United States\n- Comprehensive Anti-Money Laundering (AML) framework\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Strict reporting requirements\n- Significant penalties and criminal prosecution\n\n2. European Union\n- Unified approach through EU Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Harmonized regulations across member states\n- Enhanced customer due diligence\n- Risk-based approach\n- Focus on transparency and information sharing\n\n3. United Kingdom\n- Proceeds of Crime Act\n- Robust regulatory framework\n- Strong emphasis on financial institution compliance\n- Advanced technological monitoring systems\n\n4. Switzerland\n- Historically lenient banking secrecy laws\n- Gradually strengthening regulations\n- Increased international cooperation\n- Enhanced transparency requirements\n\n5. Singapore\n- Strict regulatory environment\n- Advanced technological monitoring\n- Severe penalties for non-compliance\n- Proactive approach to financial crime prevention\n\n6. China\n- Centralized regulatory approach\n- Growing emphasis on international standards\n- Increasing cooperation with global anti-money laundering efforts\n\nKey comparative characteristics:\n- Varying levels of regulatory strictness\n- Different enforcement mechanisms\n- Diverse technological approaches\n- Varying penalty structures",
